{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5aec72ed-a252-4819-b372-71fa47ee3f1d","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped VSTest support by default.**\n\nStarting with MSTest.Sdk **4.0.0**, the SDK exclusively targets **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (the newer runner) and **no longer generates a VSTest-compatible test host**. In 3.x, both runners were supported side-by-side.\n\nBecause `vstest.console` relies on the legacy VSTest adapter/host, it can't discover or run tests built with MSTest.Sdk 4.x out of the box.\n\n### Your options\n\n1. **Switch your CI to the new runner** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test TestProject.csproj\n   # or run the test executable directly\n   ```\n   `dotnet test` in modern SDKs auto-detects Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n2. **Re-enable VSTest compatibility** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>false</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n   and/or setting `<EnableVSTestAdapter>true</EnableVSTestAdapter>` if available, so `vstest.console` can still discover tests.\n\n3. **Pin to 3.x** until your CI tooling is updated:\n   ```xml\n   <Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the recommended path forward — Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the actively developed runner.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4dc8f8a6-7da2-452d-90e2-77ab68a62723","outputTokens":399,"requestId":"340A:183D91:108950E:134BA7B:69F41637"},"id":"e306c420-be80-41fe-84ca-88f3da098372","timestamp":"2026-05-01T02:56:02.639Z","parentId":"0f5d94dc-fcd8-4763-94cf-780e81ef513b"}
